ased","1242–Female":"1242–Deceased","1269–1360":"1269–1360","1272–Male":"1272–Deceased","1275–Male":"1275–Deceased","1216–Male":"1216–Deceased","1217–Female":"1217–Deceased","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1275":"1275","1242":"1242","1241":"1241","1272":"1272","1360":"1360","Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England","of Tal-y-llyn,Tir Ralph,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Rhydderch Ddu, Wales":"Wales","Tal-y-llyn, Merionethshire, Wales":"Tal-y-llyn, Merionethshire, Wales","of,,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Owain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened form of   O'Callaghan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Callaghan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam, Dermot, Donal, Kiernan, Niall, Conor, Donovan, John Patrick, Kieran, Siobhan, Tiernan.","Irish (Cork): from Gaelic <b>Ó Ceallacháin</b>, see   Callahan  ."]}]},{"name":"Arod","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Simplified form of   Aaron ."],"variants":[{"name":"Aaron","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the brother of Moses, who was appointed by God to be Moses' spokesman and became the first High Priest of the Israelites (Exodus 4:14–16, 7:1–2). It is of uncertain origin and meaning: most probably, like   Moses  , of Egyptian rather than Hebrew origin. The traditional derivation from Hebrew <i>har-on</i> ‘mountain of strength’ is no more than a folk etymology. The name has been in regular use from time immemorial as a Jewish name and was taken up by the Nonconformists as a Christian name in the 16th century. Since the late 1990s it has been widely popular."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Arod Arawdyr ap Owain was born in 1241, in Tal-y-llyn, Merionethshire, Wales, his father, Owain ap Arod, was 25 and his mother, Mrs. Owain ap Arod, was 24. He married Mawd verch Maredudd in 1269, in Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1241–":"1241–Surnud","1241–Male":"1241–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1242–Female":"1242–Surnud","1269–1360":"1269–1360","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1216–Male":"1216–Surnud","1217–Female":"1217–Surnud","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1275":"1275","1242":"1242","1241":"1241","1272":"1272","1360":"1360","Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England","of Tal-y-llyn,Tir Ralph,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rhydderch Ddu, Wales":"Wales","Tal-y-llyn, Merionethshire, Wales":"Tal-y-llyn, Merionethshire, Wales","of,,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1241–":"1241–Kuollut","1241–Male":"1241–Kuollut","1245–Female":"1245–Kuollut","1242–Female":"1242–Kuollut","1269–1360":"1269–1360","1272–Male":"1272–Kuollut","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1216–Male":"1216–Kuollut","1217–Female":"1217–Kuollut","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1275":"1275","1242":"1242","1241":"1241","1272":"1272","1360":"1360","Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England","of Tal-y-llyn,Tir Ralph,Breconshire,Wales":"Breconshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hereford St Owen, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Rhydderch Ddu, Wales":"Wales","Tal-y-llyn, Merionethshire, Wales":"Tal-y-llyn, Merionethshir